
1. new
.....................................

The new keyword is used to create an object in memory.

Banking Example
class BankAccount {

    String accountNumber = "ACC1001";

    void checkBalance() {
        System.out.println("Balance: ₹50,000");
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Creating an object using new
        BankAccount account = new BankAccount();

        account.checkBalance();
    }
}

Output
.....................................
Balance: ₹50,000
Real-Time Use Case

Whenever a new customer opens an account:

BankAccount account = new BankAccount();

A new object is created in the heap memory.

2. instanceof
.....................................
The instanceof operator checks whether an object belongs to a particular class or interface.

Banking Example
class Account {
}

class SavingsAccount extends Account {
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Account account = new SavingsAccount();

        System.out.println(account instanceof SavingsAccount);
        System.out.println(account instanceof Account);
    }
}

Output
.....................................
true
true
Real-Time Use Case

A banking application can determine the account type before applying business logic.

if (account instanceof SavingsAccount) {

    System.out.println("Apply Savings Interest");
}
3. super

The super keyword refers to the immediate parent class.

It is used to:

Call the parent class constructor.
Access parent class methods.
Access parent class variables.
Banking Example
class Account {

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Account Details");
    }
}

class SavingsAccount extends Account {

    void displayAccount() {

        super.display();

        System.out.println("Savings Account");
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        SavingsAccount account = new SavingsAccount();

        account.displayAccount();
    }
}

Output
.....................................
Account Details
Savings Account
Calling Parent Constructor
class Account {

    Account() {
        System.out.println("Account Created");
    }
}

class SavingsAccount extends Account {

    SavingsAccount() {

        super();

        System.out.println("Savings Account Created");
    }
}

Output
.....................................
Account Created
Savings Account Created

Real-Time Use Case

A SavingsAccount inherits common account details from the Account class.

4. this
.....................................
The this keyword refers to the current object.

It is commonly used to:

Distinguish instance variables from local variables.
Call another constructor in the same class.
Pass the current object.
Banking Example
class BankAccount {

    int accountId;
    String customerName;

    BankAccount(int accountId, String customerName) {

        this.accountId = accountId;
        this.customerName = customerName;
    }

    void display() {

        System.out.println(accountId);
        System.out.println(customerName);
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        BankAccount account =
                new BankAccount(101, "Sunil");

        account.display();
    }
}

Output
.....................................
101
Sunil

Constructor Chaining Using this()
class BankAccount {

    BankAccount() {

        this(101);

        System.out.println("Default Constructor");
    }

    BankAccount(int id) {

        System.out.println("Account ID: " + id);
    }
}

Output
.....................................
Account ID: 101
Default Constructor
Real-Time Use Case

When creating a bank account, constructor parameters initialize the object's fields.

Interview  Summary
Keyword	Banking Example
new	Create a new BankAccount object
instanceof	Check whether an account is a SavingsAccount
super	Access parent Account class methods or constructor
this	Initialize current object's account details and chain constructors


this vs super
this	super
Refers to the current object	Refers to the immediate parent object
Accesses current class members	Accesses parent class members
Calls another constructor in the same class using this()	Calls the parent constructor using super()
Used for constructor chaining	Used for inheritance
